rake(); console.log(car.getSpeed()); // Output: 0 \`\`\` 3. Полиморфизм (Polymorphism): Возможность объектов с одинаковым интерфейсом иметь различную реализацию. Например: \`\`\`javascript class Shape { calculateArea() { throw new Error('Method not implemented.'); } } class Rectangle extends Shape { constructor(width, height) { super(); this.width = width; this.height = height; } calculateArea() { return this.width * this.height; } } class Circle extends Shape { constructor(radius) { super(); this.radius = radius; } calculateArea() { return Math.PI * Math.pow(this.radius, 2); } } const rectangle = new Rectangle(5, 10); console.log(rectangle.calculateArea()); // Output: 50 const circle = new Circle(3); console.log(circle.calculateArea()); // Output: 28.274333882308138 \`\`\` 4. Абстракция (Abstraction): Сокрытие деталей реализации и предоставление только необходимых интерфейсов для взаимодействия с объектом. Например: \`\`\`javascript class Animal { constructor(name) { this.name = name; } speak() { throw new Error('Method not implemented.'); } } class Dog extends Animal { constructor(name, breed) { super(name); this.breed = breed; } speak() { console.log(this.name + ' barks.'); } } const dog = new Dog('Rex', 'Labrador'); dog.speak(); // Output: Rex barks. \`\`\` Надеюсь, эти примеры помогут вам лучше понять принципы ООП на JavaScript."},{"prompt":"iterate through structure fields in c++ 11 when fields are boost::optional using BOOST_FUSION_ADAPT_STRUCT and compare each field with threshold","completion":"To iterate through structure fields in C++11 when the fields are \`boost::optional\` using \`BOOST_FUSION_ADAPT_STRUCT\` and compare each field with a threshold, you can use the following steps: Step 1: Include the necessary headers: \`\`\`cpp #include <boost/fusion/include/adapt_struct.hpp> #include <boost/fusion/include/for_each.hpp> #include <boost/optional.hpp> \`\`\` Step 2: Define the structure with \`boost::optional\` fields: \`\`\`cpp struct Data { boost::optional<int> field1; boost::optional<double> field2; boost::optional<std::string> field3; // Add more optional fields as needed }; \`\`\` Step 3: Adapt the structure using \`BOOST_FUSION_ADAPT_STRUCT\`: \`\`\`cpp BOOST_FUSION_ADAPT_STRUCT( Data, (boost::optional<int>, field1) (boost::optional<double>, field2) (boost::optional<std::string>, field3) // Add more fields as needed ) \`\`\` Step 4: Define a functor that compares each field with a threshold: \`\`\`cpp struct ThresholdComparator { int threshold; template <typename T> void operator()(const T& field) const { if (field && *field > threshold) { // Do something if the field is greater than the threshold } } }; \`\`\` Step 5: Iterate through the fields and compare each field with the threshold: \`\`\`cpp Data data; // Create an instance of the structure int threshold = 10; // Set a threshold value boost::fusion::for_each(data, ThresholdComparator{threshold}); \`\`\` In the above code, the \`ThresholdComparator\` functor takes a threshold value during construction and overload the \`()\` operator to compare each \`boost::optional\` field with the given threshold value. The \`boost::fusion::for_each\` function is used to iterate through the fields and apply the comparison for each field."},{"prompt":"iterate through structure fields in c++ 11 when fields are boost::optional using BOOST_FUSION_ADAPT_STRUCT and compare each field with threshold taken from structure of the same type","completion":"To iterate through structure fields in C++11 when the fields are \`boost::optional\` using \`BOOST_FUSION_ADAPT_STRUCT\` and compare each field with a threshold taken from a structure of the same type, you can modify the previous steps as follows: Step 1: Include the necessary headers: \`\`\`cpp #include <boost/fusion/include/adapt_struct.hpp> #include <boost/fusion/include/for_each.hpp> #include <boost/optional.hpp> \`\`\` Step 2: Define the structure with \`boost::optional\` fields: \`\`\`cpp struct Data { boost::optional<in